75% of working mothers have maternity-related work problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger age who are planning to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and career of Spanish women', carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute of Women.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 years and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market due to maternity.
The study emphasizes that at the beginning of partner coexistence there are many differences in opinions on the number of children depending on whether they are working or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with a partner earlier, have their first child earlier, and overall have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, postpone partnerships and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with a stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years since the start of coexistence with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have spent most of their lives achieving a stable job and therefore had to postpone their coexistence and their future.
This type of profession also has a strong impact on maternity, although it has a smaller impact on the start of coexistence with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, researcher at CSIC.
Another factor influencing the age of women at the time of marriage is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at age 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
“There is yet another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education marry and give birth to their first child even before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education prefer to get a stable job, rather than marriage and the birth of the first child.
