The auxiliary system on the manual brake is already mandatory.
As in the case of the ABS anti-blocking system, this will be the case with ESP stability control,hand-brake assistive systems, all this will become a mandatory equipment for European vehicles.
In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while others have a deadline for eliminating the deficiency, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to increase pedestrian protection, working in a way that can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary manual brake system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver is down.
But it can’t always keep this pressure up to the end.
According to a study by car parts manufacturer Bosch, one-third of the drivers who had an accident did not hit the brakes before the crash and half of them did not fully use the brake power.
Up to 1,100 accidents
This assistance, on the other hand, requires a maximum from the braking system, shortens the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatal accidents could be prevented annually.
Reducing this number will be even more significant-according to calculations would avoid one in four accidents with an impact on people-after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (with the help of a radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help him increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device will operate as intensively as possible on the brakes and minimise the risk of damage.
